    <h2>
        Shorthand for if-else block (?)
    </h2>
    <p>
        The ternary operator <code>?</code> in C++ is a shorthand 
        for an if-else block. Put the condition first, followed by the operator. Next, put two 
        values separated by a <code>:</code>. If the condition is true, it will return the first value. If false, the second. 
    </p>
    <pre><code class="lang-cpp">
#include < iostream >
int main(){
    int x = 2; 
    // using ? operator 
    std::string res = x == 2 ? "x == 2" : "x != 2";
    std::cout << res << "\n";
    // x == 2

    // without ? operator 
    if (x == 2){
        res = "x == 2";
        }
    else {
        res = "x != 2";
        }
    std::cout << res;
    // x == 2
    }


    </code></pre>
